    "description": "FEA predicts construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending. Validated by direct comparison to bench testing (N=11 constructs across two laboratories). Model influence MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence MEDIUM (pedicle screw fracture leads to revision surgery, not death).",
    "intendedUse": "Demonstrate that the FEA modeling framework reproduces experimental compression-bending behavior of a non-cannulated pedicle screw construct within pre-established acceptance bounds (<10% QoI difference, E/uval < 1.96).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "decisionConsequence": "Medium",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "hasApplicabilityConstraint": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/cou/cou1-noncannulated/applicability",
      "type": "ApplicabilityConstraint",
      "name": "Applicability domain for non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw FEA",
      "description": "Model is applicable only to solid (non-cannulated) titanium-alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) pedicle screws with nominal outer diameter 7.0–8.0 mm and thread pitch 2.75–3.00 mm, tested under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending with a 10 mm offset. Extrapolation to cannulated designs, alternative alloys, or dynamic fatigue loading is explicitly out of scope and requires a separate COU assessment."
    },
    "hasOperatingEnvelope": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/cou/cou1-noncannulated/envelope",
      "type": "OperatingEnvelope",
      "name": "Operating envelope for F1717 compression-bending FEA",
      "description": "Valid operating range: axial compressive load 0–2500 N; bending moment arm 10 mm ± 0.1 mm; crosshead displacement rate 5 mm/min ± 0.5 mm/min; ambient temperature 20–25 °C; relative humidity 40–60%. Ti-6Al-4V material properties sourced from lot-specific coupon testing (UTS 950–1050 MPa, E 110–116 GPa). Screw geometry tolerance ±0.05 mm on outer diameter. Any test or simulation condition outside these bounds invalidates the credibility claim without re-assessment."
    }
  },
